# ES Rules Pull Plan

## Motivation

Resource services (bsd_sockets, httpd, sshd, etc.) currently hard-code their
policy — what endorsements a requester needs, what ports are allowed, etc.
There is no runtime mechanism for an Endorsement Service to govern these nodes.

This plan introduces a pull-based rules distribution flow where a resource
service fetches its policy from a configured ES at startup and applies it before
serving any requests.  A push path is defined but left for future implementation.

## Definitions

A **rule** is an operation name paired with an `ERDAbstractSyntaxTree` that
describes what endorsements an incoming message must carry before the service
will honour the request.  For example:

    operation: "tcp_connect"
    required_endorsements: AND(ETYPE_ACCESS=EVALUE_ACCESS_NETWORK, ETYPE_ROLE=EVALUE_ROLE_CLIENT)

A **RuleSet** is the signed, versioned collection of rules for one service node
issued by a specific ES.

## Startup Sequence

    1. Service connects to RM (existing flow)
    2. Service authenticates to RM (existing challenge/identity flow)
    3. [optional] Service performs endorsement login to ES
          - Uses BeginEndorsementRequest (existing flow, optionally over
            EncryptedPayload once encrypted_transfer is implemented)
    4. Service resolves ES node
          a. If ES NodeID is configured directly, use it
          b. Otherwise issue ResourceQuery for EVALUE_ROLE_ENDORSEMENT_SERVICE
             and use the first result
    5. Service sends GetRulesRequest to ES (service message)
    6. ES replies with GetRulesReply containing a signed RuleSet
    7. Service validates RuleSet signature against ES public key
    8. Service installs RuleSet into its PolicyEngine
    9. Service sends ResourceAdvertisement and begins serving
   10. If ES is unavailable at step 5, service retries every retry_interval_ms
       (default 30 s) indefinitely; it does NOT serve until rules are in place
       unless running in no-ES mode (ES NodeID not configured)

## Runtime Push (future)

When the ES needs to update policy, it sends a RulesPushUpdate service message
to the service node.  The service validates the signature, checks version >
current, and atomically replaces its PolicyEngine rules.  This is defined in
proto now so clients can be written to handle it, but the ES-side push trigger
is deferred.

---

## Proto Changes

### New file: endorsement_service/endorsement_service.proto

    syntax = "proto3";
    package rsp.proto;
    import "messages.proto";

    // One rule: an operation name and the endorsement tree that must be satisfied.
    message ServiceRule {
        string    operation_name          = 1;  // e.g. "tcp_connect", "tcp_listen"
        ERDAbstractSyntaxTree required    = 2;
    }

    // Signed, versioned policy issued by an ES for one service node.
    message RuleSet {
        repeated ServiceRule rules        = 1;
        uint64   version                  = 2;  // monotonically increasing
        DateTime valid_until              = 3;  // ES signs with expiry
        NodeId   issuer_node_id           = 4;  // ES that signed this
        NodeId   subject_node_id          = 5;  // which service node this applies to
        bytes    signature                = 6;  // ECDSA-P256 over canonical hash of fields 1-5
    }

    // Request sent by a service node to the ES (as google.protobuf.Any service_message).
    message GetRulesRequest {
        string   service_type             = 1;  // e.g. "bsd_sockets", "httpd", "sshd"
        uint64   current_version          = 2;  // 0 = "I have nothing"; ES may reply
                                                //   with NOT_MODIFIED if version is current
    }

    // Reply from ES.
    message GetRulesReply {
        enum Status {
            OK           = 0;
            NOT_MODIFIED = 1;  // current_version is already up to date
            NOT_FOUND    = 2;  // no rules configured for this service type
            ERROR        = 3;
        }
        Status   status                   = 1;
        RuleSet  rules                    = 2;  // populated when status == OK
        string   error_message            = 3;
    }

    // Future: ES pushes a new rule set without waiting for a pull.
    // Service validates and applies atomically.
    message RulesPushUpdate {
        RuleSet  rules                    = 1;
    }

### Canonical hash (mq_signing.cpp)

Add hashRuleSet() following the existing hashEndorsement pattern so that
RuleSet.signature can be verified offline without a proto library.

---

## New C++ Components

### common/policy/policy_engine.hpp + policy_engine.cpp

PolicyEngine stores the active RuleSet and evaluates incoming messages.

    class PolicyEngine {
    public:
        // Returns true if no rules are loaded (ES not configured = open policy).
        bool isOpen() const;

        // Returns false until rules have been loaded at least once.
        bool isLoaded() const;

        // Atomically replace rules; thread-safe.
        void update(const rsp::proto::RuleSet& ruleSet);

        // Check whether a message satisfies the rule for the named operation.
        // Returns true if:
        //   - Engine is open (no ES configured), OR
        //   - operation has no rule (default-allow), OR
        //   - The endorsement tree is satisfied by the message's endorsements.
        // Returns false and fills out_tree with the unsatisfied requirement if denied.
        bool checkRequest(const std::string& operation,
                          const rsp::proto::RSPMessage& message,
                          rsp::proto::ERDAbstractSyntaxTree* out_tree = nullptr) const;

        uint64_t version() const;
    private:
        mutable std::shared_mutex mutex_;
        std::optional<rsp::proto::RuleSet> rules_;
    };

### common/es_rules/es_rules_client.hpp + es_rules_client.cpp

Mixin that any RSPClient subclass can inherit alongside its primary base to
get the pull/retry loop for free.

    class ESRulesClient {
    public:
        struct Config {
            std::optional<rsp::NodeID> es_node_id;  // empty = discover via ResourceQuery
            uint32_t retry_interval_ms = 30000;
        };

        // Start the background fetch loop.  Blocks until rules are loaded or
        // timeout_ms elapses (0 = return immediately, caller can poll isLoaded()).
        bool startRulesFetch(Config config, uint32_t timeout_ms = 0);

        // Stop the retry loop (called on shutdown).
        void stopRulesFetch();

        bool rulesLoaded() const { return engine_.isLoaded(); }
        const PolicyEngine& policyEngine() const { return engine_; }

    protected:
        // Called on the fetch thread each time rules are successfully installed.
        // Override to react (e.g. trigger advertisement).
        virtual void onRulesLoaded(const rsp::proto::RuleSet& rules) {}

        // Subclass must implement: send a message and return the reply.
        // Provided because ESRulesClient itself doesn't own a transport.
        virtual bool sendAndAwaitReply(const rsp::proto::RSPMessage& req,
                                       rsp::proto::RSPMessage& reply,
                                       uint32_t timeout_ms) = 0;

        PolicyEngine engine_;

    private:
        void fetchLoop(Config config);
        bool tryFetch(const Config& config);
        std::optional<rsp::NodeID> resolveES(const Config& config);

        std::thread fetchThread_;
        std::atomic<bool> stopping_ = false;
        std::mutex loadedMutex_;
        std::condition_variable loadedCv_;
    };

### resource_service/resource_service.hpp (modified)

Add optional ESRulesClient integration to the ResourceService base:

    // Call before connectToResourceManager to enable ES rules pull.
    // If not called, service runs with open policy (backwards compatible).
    void configureESRules(ESRulesClient::Config config, uint32_t startup_timeout_ms = 0);

Modify the existing `sendResourceAdvertisement` call path so that if ES rules
are configured, advertisement is deferred until `rulesLoaded()` returns true
(the fetch loop unblocks it).  If startup_timeout_ms > 0, the service logs a
warning and continues without rules after the timeout (degraded mode).

### ES-side: EndorsementService (modified)

Add handler for GetRulesRequest in `handleNodeSpecificMessage`.

The ES holds a per-service-type rule set configuration loaded from a config
file or set programmatically via a new API:

    void EndorsementService::setRules(const std::string& service_type,
                                      const rsp::proto::RuleSet& rules);

On receiving GetRulesRequest:
- Look up rules by service_type
- If version matches current_version, reply NOT_MODIFIED
- Otherwise sign the RuleSet and reply with OK + rules

Rule set config format (JSON, loaded at startup):

    {
      "bsd_sockets": {
        "version": 1,
        "valid_hours": 24,
        "rules": [
          {
            "operation": "tcp_connect",
            "required": "AND(ETYPE_ACCESS=EVALUE_ACCESS_NETWORK)"
          },
          {
            "operation": "tcp_listen",
            "required": "AND(ETYPE_ROLE=EVALUE_ROLE_RESOURCE_SERVICE)"
          }
        ]
      }
    }

The text format uses the existing `endorsement_text.hpp` parser.

---

## Resource Service Integration

### BsdSocketsResourceService

1. Inherit ESRulesClient alongside ResourceService (or hold it as a member).
2. In handleConnectTCPRequest / handleListenTCPRequest, call
   `policyEngine().checkRequest("tcp_connect", message)` before dispatching.
   On deny, send back an `EndorsementNeeded` message with the unsatisfied tree.
3. Config struct gains `ESRulesClient::Config es_rules`.
4. `buildResourceAdvertisement()` can optionally include the rule version so
   clients know which policy version is active.

Same pattern applies to httpd and sshd resource services.

